  35  """* 
  36  ** Specifies the type of symbol used by a curve. GChart 
  37  ** includes a <tt>LINE</tt> symbol type (suitable for solidly 
  38  ** connected line charts), various "box" symbol types 
  39  ** (suitable for scatter and dotted-line charts), 
  40  ** horizontal and vertical bars that extend to axis limits 
  41  ** or a specified baseline (suitable for bar and area charts), 
  42  ** and pie slices (suitable for pie charts) in these 
  43  ** symbol types. Thus, choosing a curve's symbol type has a 
  44  ** bigger impact on the kind of chart you create than in 
  45  ** other charting APIs you may have used. 
  46  ** 
  47  ** <p> One advantage of this symbol type based approach: you 
  48  ** can place multiple pies, lines and/or bars on a single 
  49  ** chart simply by creating multiple curves whose associated 
  50  ** symbols have appropriately different symbol types. 
  51  ** 
  52  ** <p> Note that, for line, area, or pie charts, the exact 
  53  ** look of the non-rectangular aspects (connecting lines, 
  54  ** filled-in areas, etc.) of these symbols in the chart is 
  55  ** largely governed by the host <tt>Symbol</tt>'s 
  56  ** <tt>fillSpacing</tt> and <tt>fillThickness</tt> 
  57  ** properties. 
  58  ** 
  59  ** <p> For instance, with the default <tt>fillThickness</tt> 
  60  ** of 0 for the <tt>BOX_CENTER</tt> symbol, curves display 
  61  ** only explicitly specified data points, without any 
  62  ** connecting lines between them. But, if you set 
  63  ** <tt>fillThickness</tt> to 1, GChart interpolates a series 
  64  ** of 1 pixel by 1 pixel rectangular "dots" between successive 
  65  ** data points, with an intra-dot spacing defined by the 
  66  ** symbol's <tt>fillSpacing</tt> setting.  <p> 
  67  ** 
  68  ** Since v2.5, a <tt>fillSpacing==0</tt> setting, with the 
  69  ** special meaning of "continuous filling", is allowed. If an 
  70  ** external canvas library has been plugged into GChart via 
  71  ** <tt>setCanvasFactory</tt>, 
  72  ** higher quality, continuously filled pie, line, and area charts 
  73  ** can be produced via the combination: <tt>fillSpacing==0</tt> and 
  74  ** <tt>fillThickness > 0</tt> along with one of the pie, line, or 
  75  ** bar symbol types described below.<p> 
  76  ** 
  77  ** You must select each curve's symbol type from the predefined 
  78  ** set of supported types listed in the "Field Summary" 
  79  ** section below. The default symbol type is <tt>BOX_CENTER</tt>. 
  80  ** 
  81  ** @see Curve#getSymbol getSymbol 
  82  ** @see Symbol#setSymbolType setSymbolType 
  83  ** @see Symbol#setFillSpacing setFillSpacing 
  84  ** @see Symbol#setFillThickness setFillThickness 
  85  ** @see Symbol Symbol 
  86  ** 
  87  *"""

  90      """ 
  91      * For efficiency during hit testing, points get separated 
  92      * into bins associated with adjacent vertical 
  93      * (or horizontal) bands that cover the plot area. 
  94      * <p> 
  95      * 
  96      * Subclasses (such as those for producing horizontal bar 
  97      * charts) whose rendered symbols do not have a fixed width 
  98      * across all the points on a single curve, MUST set this 
  99      * field to True within their constructors, because 
 100      * the hit testing approach assumes fixed "thickness" 
 101      * symbols for simplicity/efficiency. 
 102      * <p> 
 103      * 
 104      * Subclasses that have both a fixed width and height MAY 
 105      * set this to True if they are typically used in a way 
 106      * that tends to make horizontal banding a better (= tends 
 107      * to place same # of points in each band) binning strategy. 
 108      * 
 109      * <p> 
 110      * 
 111      * If <tt>None</tt>, GChart uses a simple heuristic that assumes 
 112      * that a brush that is wider than high implies developer is 
 113      * trying to let user distinguish finer y differences, and thus 
 114      * our bands should separate points more finely (and hence allow 
 115      * for faster band-indexed hit testing) if we use horizontal 
 116      * banding in this case (and vertical otherwise). 
 117      * <p> 
 118      * 
 119      * See the <tt>bandSeparatePoints</tt> method for more info. 
 120      * 
 121      """

 157      # play similar role as same-named fields of AnnotationLocation 
 158      """ 
 159      * If a symbol's left, right, top, or bottom edge 
 160      * represents the x or y location associated with this 
 161      * symbol, the corresponding pixel paddings are 0. 
 162      * 
 163      * If a position 1/2 pixel to the right, left, below, or 
 164      * above (respectively) those edges represents the position 
 165      * of the x or y in question, the values are 0.5. 
 166      * 
 167      * Why is this needed? Because GChart uses 1 px gridlines 
 168      * whose center represents the point associated with the 
 169      * gridline, and to get a corresponding edge to perfectly 
 170      * overlay a gridline when its associated position is 
 171      * the same as that gridline, we need to associated the 
 172      * position of the represented x or y coordinate not 
 173      * with the symbol's box edge itself, but rather 
 174      * with a position 1/2 px towards the center of the 
 175      * symbol. If you don't specify an extra half pixel 
 176      * for, say, a vertical bar, it won't align right 
 177      * on top of gridlines when it has the same height 
 178      * as the associated gridline. 
 179      * <p> 
 180      * 
 181      * In effect, we deliberately add a 1/2 px error to 
 182      * certain symbols so that they appear to line up 
 183      * perfectly with the gridlines. 
 184      * 
 185      """

3304  ** Draw a pie slice whose area is shaded using either 
3305  ** vertical bars or horizontal bars--whichever 
3306  ** renders the slice more efficiently. Specifically, pie 
3307  ** slices that are wider than they are tall use horizontal 
3308  ** shading and pie slices that are taller than they are

3310  ** the number of shading bars (and thus memory and time) 
3311  ** required to render the pie slice.

3314  ** 
3315  ** The distance between corresponding edges of successive 
3316  ** bars is governed by the symbol's fill spacing property

3318  ** fill thickness property; the border and background of 
3319  ** each shading bar are defined by the symbol's border

3324  ** formula: 
3325  ** 
3326  ** <p>

3328  **   <pre>

3339  ** radius is the one associated with the circle that 
3340  ** circumscribes the symbol, that is, the smallest circle 
3341  ** that is big enough to completely contain the symbol's 
3342  ** width/height defined bounding rectangle. Equivalently,

3344  ** length of the diagonal across the symbol's bounding
